<p>
  Imagine you are trying to crack a password. One single character, just the
  letter A, 64 possibilities in all. You keep guessing at random, and soon
  enough you hit it.
</p>
<p>Now the password is two characters. It takes longer. But you still get there.</p>
<p>
  Now make it a million characters long. The number of possible passwords
  runs 1.8 million digits long, and the odds of guessing right shrink to
  almost nothing. Almost. Not quite zero.
</p>
<p>
  Here is where it turns strange. Give yourself infinite attempts, and
  cracking that million-character password does not just become likely. It
  becomes certain.
</p>
<p>Given infinite attempts, everything that can happen will happen.</p>
<p>
  That is the heart of the paradox. Set infinite monkeys at infinite
  typewriters, hammering keys at random for infinite time, and one of them
  types the complete works of Shakespeare. Every word, every play, every
  sonnet, perfect.
</p>
<p>
  Not because the monkeys are clever. Not because they are trying. Only
  because infinite time turns even the most impossible thing into something
  inevitable.
</p>
<p>
  And it does not stop there. Every book that could ever be written appears.
  The ones not written yet. The ones describing things that have not
  happened yet.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p>
  Here is the part the story leaves out. The same infinity that types
  Shakespeare also types a billion broken copies: the same play with one
  line ruined, one date changed, one lie set exactly where the truth should
  be. The masterpiece is in there, buried in an endless landfill of noise
  that sounds almost true.
</p>
<p>
  So maybe the rare thing was never the text. Maybe the rare thing is the
  reader who can tell the difference. You do not need every possible book.
  You need the one worth carrying.
</p>
<hr class="post-divider" />
<p><em>If everything can appear, what makes one thing real to you?</em></p>
<p>The paradox is not really about monkeys. It is about infinity.</p>
<p>
  Infinity does not mean very very large.
  <strong>It means the impossible becomes inevitable.</strong>
</p>
